Kent Beck wrote:
&gt; David,
&gt; 
&gt; I think that the framework should continue to work in as many situations as
&gt; possible. If a listener throws an exception, the framework should deal with
&gt; it. Contributing to Eclipse calls this the Safe Platform Rule: &quot;As the
&gt; provider of an extension point, you must protect yourself against
&gt; misbehavior on the part of extenders.&quot; Here is the test I came up with that
&gt; I think should pass (and doesn&#39;t currently):
&gt; 
&gt;       int count;
&gt;      
&gt;       class FailingListener implements TestListener {
&gt;             public void testRunStarted(int testCount) {
&gt;                   count++;
&gt;                   throw new Error();
&gt;             }
&gt; 
&gt;             public void testRunFinished(Runner runner) {
&gt;             }
&gt; 
&gt;             public void testStarted(Object test, String name) {
&gt;             }
&gt; 
&gt;             public void testFinished(Object test, String name) {
&gt;             }
&gt; 
&gt;             public void testFailure(Failure failure) {
&gt;             }
&gt; 
&gt;             public void testIgnored(Method method) {
&gt;             }
&gt;       }
&gt;      
&gt;       public static class OneTest {
&gt;             @Test public void nothing() {}
&gt;       }
&gt;      
&gt;       @Test public void failingListener() {
&gt;             count= 0;
&gt;             Runner runner= new Runner();
&gt;             runner.addListener(new FailingListener());
&gt;             runner.addListener(new FailingListener());
&gt;             runner.run(OneTest.class);
&gt;             assertEquals(2, count);
&gt;       }
&gt;      
&gt;      
&gt;       public static junit.framework.Test suite() {
&gt;             return new JUnit4TestAdapter(TestListenerTest.class);
&gt;       }
&gt; 
&gt; I am working on an implementation. Alternatively, should the count be 1?

If you&#39;re wondering whether the new FailingListeners should be counted 
as equal, I believe not. They aren&#39;t Value Objects, so I don&#39;t think 
they should be compared with value equality.

If you&#39;re wondering about something else, then ignore me and wait for an 
intelligent reply.
